Oral presentation";
Human brain consists of more than 100 billion cells called “neurons.” Each neuron in the brain translates genetic information from chromosomes in nucleus through a process called “transcription” and the transcribed information is then “translated” into amino acid chain which is folded up into proteins. Most of the produced proteins have specific functions in neurons. The massive amount of information regarding function of the protein is accumulated in public databases and literatures. Genome informatics and systems biology are relatively new fields in biology, both of which are powerful approaches to integrate the massive amount of information and understand biological phenomena, often in quantitative manner. Genome informatics provides a computational method to analyze genetic information and systems biology, on the other hand, integrates physiological information regarding the function of the proteins into a mathematical model to represent dynamic behavior of the cells including neurons for simulation and prediction.
";
This course provides the basic concepts of genome informatics and the systems biology through analysis of various biological phenomena in neuroscience. Students are expected to read textbooks and/or selected research papers every week to learn basics of neuroscience in the first half. In the second half, students will learn computational methods to analyze neural genes and also conduct simulation of neurons via E-Cell System.
